**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add Problem Details + custom handler
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must be early in the pipeline
app.UseExceptionHandler();

// Your endpoints — no try-catch needed
app.MapGet("/items/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    if (id < 0) throw new ArgumentException("ID must be positive.");
    if (id == 0) throw new KeyNotFoundException("Item not found.");
    if (id == 99) throw new InvalidOperationException("Item is archived.");
    return Results.Ok(new { Id = id, Name = "Widget" });
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

- `UseExceptionHandler()` catches any unhandled exception globally
- `IExceptionHandler` (available in .NET 8+) gives you typed access to the exception
- For 500s, `exception.Message` is suppressed to avoid leaking internals
- The response `Content-Type` is automatically `application/problem+json`

**Example 404 response:**
```json
{
  "status": 404,
  "title": "Not Found",
  "detail": "Item not found."
}
```

If you're on .NET 7, replace `IExceptionHandler` with a custom middleware that does the same switch/write logic inside `app.UseExceptionHandler(cfg => cfg.Run(...))`.
